          "body": "After the theological lightning of 2:1-38, Luke does something startling — he sends Jesus to Nazareth and silences the narrative for twelve years. The bracketing summary statements (2:40 and 2:52) are nearly identical: He grew, became strong, increased in wisdom, the grace of God / favor with God and men was upon Him. Luke is asserting genuine human development — not a divine appearance in human costume, but real cognitive, physical, and social maturation. Then at twelve, the temple scene erupts. Jesus listens, asks questions, gives answers that astonish the rabbis (2:46-47). When His parents finally find Him after three days (a detail not lost on Luke 24:7), He gives His first recorded words: 'Did you not know that I had to be in My Father's house?' (2:49). 'Had to' (dei) is Luke's signature word for divine necessity (cf. 9:22; 13:33; 24:7, 26). Jesus at twelve already operates under the same dei that will drive Him to the cross. Mary heard 'your father' in her own mouth (2:48); Jesus replied 'My Father' (2:49) — gently, decisively, relocating His ultimate paternity. He then 'went down with them...and continued in subjection to them' (2:51). The Son who knows the Father submits to His earthly parents — perfect humanity from the start."
